      Should Elon Musk sell $20 billion worth of Tesla stock or what?
   =20
 =20
Let him know what you think! Actually it=E2=80=99s too late.=C2=A0He took a=
 poll over the weekend, on Twitter, and the winning answer was =E2=80=9CYes=
.=E2=80=9D The poll was legally binding?=C2=A0Discussion questions!=09Is it=
 consistent with Musk=E2=80=99s fiduciary duties as chief executive officer=
 and  controlling shareholder of Tesla Inc. to sell or not sell $20.8 billi=
on worth of stock =E2=80=94=C2=A01.7% of the company[1] =E2=80=94 based on =
the results of a Twitter poll? In answering this question, keep in mind tha=
t Tesla has a $1.2 trillion market capitalization and essentially free acce=
ss to limitless capital, in part=C2=A0because=C2=A0Musk does so much entert=
aining reckless nonsense on Twitter. One could reverse the question: Would =
it be a   breach of his fiduciary duties=C2=A0not=C2=A0to make whimsical de=
cisions like this on Twitter?=09The poll closed   Sunday afternoon; 57.9% o=
f the 3.5 million votes cast were in favor of selling.=C2=A0Assuming that M=
usk will in fact abide by the results and sell $20.8 billion worth of=C2=A0=
stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0roughly one day=E2=80=99s volume =E2=80=94=C2=A0would =
you have expected the stock to go up or down today? (Try to answer before l=
ooking=C2=A0at what it actually did!) It actually   went down: It opened do=
wn about 6%, though then it recovered a bit during the morning. This strike=
s me as a boringly conventional answer. I sort of figured it would go up. S=
ure he=E2=80=99s selling stock but, like, as a joke?=09If you were a Tesla =
shareholder, how would you have voted in this poll? (Would your answer chan=
ge if you were an index fund manager?) If you were a Tesla short seller, ho=
w would you have voted in this poll? If you were a Tesla short seller and y=
ou programmed a bot to open a million Twitter accounts and vote in this pol=
l, would anyone have any legal claims against you? What about if you were a=
 Tesla long investor? A Tesla board member? Elon Musk? Jeff Bezos?=09If you=
 had to overgeneralize and say =E2=80=9Cthe reason that a majority of=C2=A0=
3.5 million people on Twitter voted for Elon Musk to dump $20 billion of st=
ock was _________,=E2=80=9D what one reason would you put=C2=A0in that blan=
k? They are fans of Elon Musk and want him to have some cash to treat himse=
lf to something nice? They are haters of Elon Musk and want him to be less =
rich? They are buyers of Tesla stock and want some more supply so they can =
have an attractive buying opportunity? They are skeptics of Tesla stock and=
 want some more supply so the price will go down? They are believers in tax=
ing billionaires=E2=80=99 unrealized capital gains and, in the absence of a=
 tax code that does that, they want the world=E2=80=99s richest person=C2=
=A0to voluntarily realize some of his gains and pay taxes on them? They are=
 people who were bored on Twitter over the weekend and, presented with a po=
ll, chose the more chaotic answer?=C2=A0=09Musk has  22.8 million Tesla sto=
ck options that expire in August 2022, with a strike price of $6.24. Tesla =
closed on Friday at $1,222.09. Those options are very in-the-money and he w=
ill need to exercise them between now and next August. Musk=E2=80=99s optio=
ns are presumably =E2=80=9Cnon-qualified=E2=80=9D options, meaning that he =
will owe ordinary income tax on essentially the full value of the stock at =
the time he exercises them.[2] As=C2=A0CNBC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Jessica Bursztyn=
sky and Lora Kolodny noted=C2=A0on Saturday: =E2=80=9CMusk previously said =
he was likely to sell =E2=80=98a huge block=E2=80=99 of his options in the =
fourth quarter. At an appearance at the Code Conference in September, Musk =
said when his stock options expire at Tesla, his marginal tax rate will be =
over 50 percent and that he was already planning to sell soon. =E2=80=98I h=
ave a bunch of options that are expiring early next year, so ... a huge blo=
ck of options will sell in Q4 =E2=80=94 because I have to or they=E2=80=99l=
l expire,=E2=80=99 Musk said at the conference.=E2=80=9D (They don=E2=80=99=
t actually expire until next August; he apparently wants=C2=A0to do it in t=
he fourth quarter of 2021 because he=E2=80=99s  worried about tax rates goi=
ng up next year.) At Friday=E2=80=99s closing price, Musk would have income=
 of about $27.8 billion when he exercises these options; at a 50% tax rate =
he=E2=80=99ll owe about $13.9 billion in taxes. I guess this is=C2=A0more o=
f a comment than a question. Maybe the question is: Was his poll over the w=
eekend for real, or was he going to sell stock anyway to cover taxes on opt=
ions exercise, and he wanted to dress it up a little in a fun poll?=09Recon=
sider your answer to Question 1 in light of your answer to Question 5. If h=
e was going to sell $20 billion of stock anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0to pay taxes=
 on his huge award of new Tesla shares, to take some profits, to buy grocer=
ies, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0isn=E2=80=99t it=C2=A0better, for his sharehol=
ders, to turn it into a dumb Twitter stunt? If the CEO of a company just du=
mps some stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly if that CEO is Elon Musk, whose =
=09=09tweets determine the value of all sorts of companies and cryptocurren=
cies =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the stock will go down. But if he makes a fun game=
 out of it maybe that will confound those expectations?=C2=A0=09If Musk doe=
s=C2=A0not=C2=A0abide by the results of this poll =E2=80=94 if he does not =
sell 10% of his stock, as a majority of 3.5 million randos on Twitter told =
him to=C2=A0=E2=80=94 would that be securities fraud? In answering this que=
stion, consider who might have been defrauded, and how. Consider also how m=
uch time Musk should get to abide by the poll: If he sells 1% of his stock =
per year for 10 years, would that count?=09If your answer=C2=A0to Question =
7 was =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0i.e., if you think it would be s=
ecurities fraud for Musk to tweet a poll and say he=E2=80=99d abide by the =
result=C2=A0and then not do it =E2=80=94=C2=A0then does that mean that the =
Twitter poll was in fact legally binding?=C2=A0More generally, is anything =
that the chief executive officer of a public company says on Twitter legall=
y binding, because if it is not true then  that=E2=80=99s securities fraud?=
=09If the poll had gone the other way (i.e. the majority voted no)=C2=A0and=
 Musk had not obeyed=C2=A0the results =E2=80=94=C2=A0if, for instance, he s=
old millions of shares in the next few months to pay income taxes on the ex=
ercise of stock options that expire next year, as he has said=C2=A0he will=
=C2=A0(see Question 5)=C2=A0=E2=80=94 would that be fraud? On whom, and how=
? Again, consider how long you would want him to be restricted for, and on =
how much stock: If he sold stock in January, would that violate the spirit =
of the poll? If he sold 5% of his stock? If he sold only after exercising o=
ptions that would otherwise expire, and only to pay taxes due on that exerc=
ise?=09If he was going to sell the stock anyway to pay taxes on options exe=
rcise, but did this poll as a distraction, is that somehow fraud? =E2=80=9C=
You were going to sell stock to pay your tax bill like a rational person, b=
ut instead you pretended to sell stock based on a Twitter poll like a reckl=
ess weirdo, and I believed you and was deceived=E2=80=9D? Would that be a m=
isrepresentation of a=C2=A0material=C2=A0fact? Who would have a claim for d=
amages against him?=09Is this Twitter poll consistent with   Tesla=E2=80=99=
s settlement with the Securities and Exchange Commission requiring Musk to =
pre-clear tweets that might be material to shareholders with a Tesla securi=
ties lawyer? In answering this question, keep in mind that (1) there=E2=80=
=99s   no way he cleared this tweet with a lawyer, lol,=C2=A0and (2) the se=
ttlement   was modified in 2019, after Musk previously   ignored it, to req=
uire pre-clearance only for certain specific=C2=A0categories of tweets, one=
 of which is tweets about =E2=80=9Cevents regarding the Company=E2=80=99s s=
ecurities (including Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition or disposition of the Compa=
ny=E2=80=99s securities).=E2=80=9D This is that, no?=C2=A0=09Assume hypothe=
tically that Musk has negative inside information about Tesla. If he tweets=
 this poll, the majority votes yes, and he sells stock, has he committed in=
sider trading? Has he sold stock =E2=80=9Con the basis of=E2=80=9D negative=
 inside information, if the proximate cause of his selling is that=C2=A0Twi=
tter people told him to?=09Same as Question 12 except assume that Musk had =
no negative inside information when he tweeted the poll, but=C2=A0got=C2=A0=
negative inside information between the time of his tweet and the time of h=
is sales. (This is funniest if you assume he got the inside information, li=
ke, Sunday morning, while the poll=C2=A0was still open.) Is=C2=A0that=C2=A0=
insider trading? Or is this in effect =09a 10b5-1 plan: =E2=80=9CWhen I had=
 no inside information, I committed to do what Twitter told me to, so you c=
an=E2=80=99t hold me responsible for my trading now=E2=80=9D? (Consider tha=
t  Rule 10b-5(c)(1)(B) requires a 10b5-1 plan to give up discretion as to d=
ate, time and size of trades.)=09Back in 2018, Musk pretended he was going =
to take Tesla private,  in part because he wanted to run Tesla =E2=80=9Cfre=
e from as much distraction and short-term thinking as possible,=E2=80=9D an=
d he thought that a public listing was a distraction. I   suggested at the =
time that Musk himself, addicted as he is to Twitter and controversy and no=
nsense, might be unusually distractible and/or distracting, and that the pu=
blic listing was not the problem. Based on this weekend, who was right? Doe=
s Twitter=E2=80=99s public listing tempt Musk to do stunts like this? It=E2=
=80=99s relatively easy for him to sell $20 billion of public stock so, sur=
e, what the heck, put that out to vote on Twitter. Or would he be doing stu=
nts like this even if Tesla was private? =E2=80=9CShould I sell $20 billion=
 more of stock to the Saudis in private transactions,=E2=80=9D he could hav=
e asked his Twitter followers, or =E2=80=9Cshould I take Tesla public again=
 with a special purpose acquisition company and sell $20 billion of my own =
stock?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09As Musk mentioned, there was briefly some pretty   =
hypothetical discussion about taxing billionaires on their unrealized capit=
al gains, but it is obviously not going to happen. So Musk does not need to=
 sell any Tesla stock to pay any unrealized-gains taxes; that is a pure dis=
traction. If he sells $20 billion of stock he will have to pay let=E2=80=99=
s say  $4 billion=C2=A0of capital gains taxes (on the gains he=C2=A0realize=
s=C2=A0in that sale) and will have about $16 billion or so left over. (Assu=
me =E2=80=94=C2=A0counterfactually? =E2=80=94=C2=A0that he does this withou=
t, or=C2=A0rather=C2=A0before, exercising any stock options, so he won=E2=
=80=99t need that money to pay taxes on his stock-option exercise.[3]) Shou=
ld he use that $16 billion to buy (1)  Bitcoin, (2) Dogecoin, (3) Shiba Inu=
 coin, (4) Hertz Global Holdings Inc. (market cap $16.2 billion!), (5) Game=
Stop Corp. (market cap $16.3 billion!), (6) a tasteful collection of non-fu=
ngible tokens, (7) more Tesla stock, or (8) other?=09On Saturday, Senator R=
on Wyden, who sponsored the proposal to tax billionaires on their unrealize=
d capital gains,  tweeted that =E2=80=9Cwhether or not the world=E2=80=99s =
wealthiest man pays any taxes at all shouldn=E2=80=99t depend on the result=
s of a Twitter poll.=E2=80=9D Does=C2=A0he have a point? As Musk says, =E2=
=80=9Cthe only way for me to pay taxes personally is to sell stock,=E2=80=
=9D which is (normally) his decision.[4]=C2=A0He is the richest person in t=
he world, and he gets to decide whether he wants to pay any taxes, and when=
 and how much.=C2=A0Or, in this case, 3.5 million people on Twitter get to =
decide.=09On Sunday, Musk  replied to Wyden=E2=80=99s tweet=C2=A0with a   c=
rude=C2=A0sexual critique of=C2=A0Wyden=E2=80=99s Twitter profile picture. =
Was that a good idea? Who would you say won the argument?=C2=A0=09=E2=80=9C=
Elon Musk is Now =E2=80=98Lorde Edge=E2=80=99 From Trollheim on Twitter,=E2=
=80=9D is   another Bloomberg headline from this morning. Billy Markus, =E2=
=80=9Cthe creator of Dogecoin, guessed it=E2=80=99s an anagram for =E2=80=
=98Elder Doge.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Feel free to discuss that one.
