      The Theranos defense
   =20
 =20
If you go to someone and say =E2=80=9Cplease invest a million dollars in my=
 company, it is a good company,=E2=80=9D and they say =E2=80=9Cyou seem lik=
e a nice person, here is a million dollars,=E2=80=9D and they give you the =
money and you spend it on restaurants and gambling, and they bring you to c=
ourt for fraud, I suppose it is a defense for you to say =E2=80=9Cbut you n=
ever=C2=A0asked me=C2=A0what I was going to spend the money on.=E2=80=9D An=
d they=E2=80=99ll say, like, =E2=80=9Cyou told me it was for your company a=
nd that it was a good company,=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99ll say =E2=80=9Cwel=
l, it was=C2=A0a good company,=C2=A0for me; it paid for a lot of good meals=
.=E2=80=9D This is not, I think, a completely trivial defense, though this =
is not legal advice and I wouldn=E2=80=99t necessarily try it. But the ques=
tion in a fraud case is whether you lied about material facts and whether t=
he investor=C2=A0justifiably relied on those lies. If you were careful not =
to actually lie, and the investor forgot to ask you any questions about you=
r plans, there=E2=80=99s probably no fraud. Even if you did lie a bit, but =
the investor had no good reason to believe you, you might not be guilty of =
fraud.You could imagine more complicated variants. For instance, your compa=
ny could have a written business plan that says =E2=80=9Cthe plan is to spe=
nd all the money we raise at restaurants and casinos,=E2=80=9D and it could=
 have audited financial statements showing zero revenue, millions of cash i=
nflows from investors, and identical outflows to restaurants and casinos. A=
nd then when potential investors heard your pitch and said =E2=80=9Cokay se=
nd me your business plan and financial statements,=E2=80=9D you could say =
=E2=80=9Cno, those are too secret to share with investors, but trust me the=
y are very good.=E2=80=9D And then when you end up in court you can be like=
 =E2=80=9Cwell, again, they=C2=A0were=C2=A0good, for me.=E2=80=9D And the i=
nvestor =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look, it=C2=A0is=C2=A0kind of bad for the investor t=
o give you money without seeing the financials? Like, sure you told them th=
at they couldn=E2=80=99t see the financials, but they could have walked awa=
y at that point! At some point, if someone wants to be defrauded badly enou=
gh, it is almost not fraud to take their money?At the New York Times,=C2=A0=
Erin Griffith had a funny story about the fraud trial of Theranos Inc. foun=
der Elizabeth Holmes:As investors have testified at Ms. Holmes=E2=80=99s tr=
ial, a central tension has emerged around due diligence. Could these invest=
ors have avoided disaster if they had simply done better research on Theran=
os? Or were they doomed because their research was based on lies? ...Ms. Ho=
lmes=E2=80=99s lawyers have needled Theranos=E2=80=99s investors for their =
oversights, aiming to convince the jury that the investors were the ones at=
 fault for not digging into Ms. Holmes=E2=80=99 claims. =E2=80=A6The strate=
gy has sometimes veered into condescension. That was evident last week when=
 Lance Wade, a lawyer for Ms. Holmes, asked [DeVos family-office investment=
 manager Lisa]=C2=A0Peterson, an investment professional, if she was famili=
ar with the concept of due diligence.=E2=80=9CYou understand that=E2=80=99s=
 a typical thing to do in investing?=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=A6[Christophe=
r] Lucas=E2=80=99s firm, Black Diamond Ventures, invested around $7 million=
 into Theranos, despite not getting access to its financial information or =
examining all of its corporate records. This was unusual, Mr. Lucas testifi=
ed on Thursday, but Ms. Holmes told him the information was sensitive becau=
se a leak could =E2=80=9Cgive competitors a chance to crush the company.=E2=
=80=9DThat secrecy extended to due diligence. Ms. Peterson testified that s=
he was scared Ms. Holmes would cut her firm out of the deal if they dug dee=
per into the details of Theranos=E2=80=99s business.=E2=80=9CWe were very c=
areful not to circumvent things and upset Elizabeth,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=
=80=9CIf we did too much, we wouldn=E2=80=99t be invited back to invest.=E2=
=80=9DA lot of this stuff comes down to market norms, on both sides.  Part =
of Holmes=E2=80=99s defense is =E2=80=9Cthat exaggeration is part of Silico=
n Valley=E2=80=99s startup culture=E2=80=9D: Sure she did a certain amount =
of fake-it-till-you-make-it, but everyone in startups does that and investo=
rs could not have been deceived by it. But part of the argument=C2=A0agains=
t=C2=A0her is that her investors=C2=A0did justifiably rely on her sketchy p=
itch, without pushing to do real due diligence, because in a deal world dri=
ven by fear of missing out on the next big thing, that was actually a norma=
l way for an investor to operate.
