right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscri=
be to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] Mu=
sk owns 170,492,985 shares in a revocable trust, about 17% of the=C2=A01,00=
4,264,852 shares outstanding. At Friday=E2=80=99s closing price of $1,222.0=
9, those shares are worth about $208 billion.=C2=A0The company=E2=80=99s di=
sclosure shows him beneficially owning 73.5 million more shares underlying =
options; I=E2=80=99m not sure if he counts those options=C2=A0in =E2=80=9Cm=
y Tesla stock=E2=80=9D for purposes of, uh, this legally binding Twitter po=
ll. But if he does then he=E2=80=99d be selling almost $30 billion worth.[2=
] Strictly the difference between the market price and the strike price is =
treated as taxable compensation, but here the strike price is 0.5% of the m=
arket price so basically the whole amount will be taxable. Many executive s=
tock options are taxed differently =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are =E2=80=9Cstatuto=
ry incentive stock options=E2=80=9D and don=E2=80=99t trigger taxes on exer=
cise =E2=80=94=C2=A0but Musk does not seem to have statutory ISOs. There co=
uld be various reasons for that, but one obvious possible explanation=C2=A0=
is that Musk owns (and has long owned) more than 10% of Tesla=E2=80=99s sto=
ck, and the Internal Revenue Code=E2=80=99s requirements for statutory ISOs=
 include that the grantee =E2=80=9Cdoes not own stock possessing more than =
10 percent of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock of th=
e employer corporation.=E2=80=9D So he will have to pay taxes on exercise.=
=C2=A0He could do that by borrowing against his shares (as he already does =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0more than half of his Tesla stock is =E2=80=9Cpledged as col=
lateral to secure certain personal indebtedness=E2=80=9D) or else by sellin=
g billions of dollars worth of stock. A fairly common approach, if you owe =
50% taxes on a stock options exercise, is to sell half of the stock that yo=
u get, so without this Twitter poll you=E2=80=99d expect Musk to be selling=
 11 million shares soon anyway.[3] See Question 5. Again,=C2=A0the options =
do not expire until next summer so there is no particular need to do it now=
, except if he's worried about tax rates going up next year.[4]=C2=A0 Excep=
t when he has options expiring. See Question 5.
