<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The Theranos defense</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you go to someone and say =E2=80=9C=
please invest a million dollars in my company, it is a good company,=E2=80=
=9D and they say =E2=80=9Cyou seem like a nice person, here is a million do=
llars,=E2=80=9D and they give you the money and you spend it on restaurants=
 and gambling, and they bring you to court for fraud, I suppose it is a def=
ense for you to say =E2=80=9Cbut you never=C2=A0<em>asked me=C2=A0</em>what=
 I was going to spend the money on.=E2=80=9D And they=E2=80=99ll say, like,=
 =E2=80=9Cyou told me it was for your company and that it was a good compan=
y,=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99ll say =E2=80=9Cwell, it <em>was=C2=A0</em>a go=
od company,=C2=A0<em>for me</em>; it paid for a lot of good meals.=E2=80=9D=
 This is not, I think, a completely trivial defense, though this is not leg=
al advice and I wouldn=E2=80=99t necessarily try it. But the question in a =
fraud case is whether you lied about material facts and whether the investo=
r=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25625218.27=
6657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud29sZnBvcHBlcmJsb2cuY29tL2Jsb2cvMjAxNy84LzcvYS1xdWljay=
1sb29rLWF0LXRoZS1lbGVtZW50cy1vZi1zZWN1cml0aWVzLWZyYXVkLWNsYWltLXVuZGVyLXNlY=
y1ydWxlLTEwYi01LXB0Mg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3510ada6" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">justifiabl=
y relied</a> on those lies. If you were careful not to actually lie, and th=
e investor forgot to ask you any questions about your plans, there=E2=80=99=
s probably no fraud. Even if you did lie a bit, but the investor had no goo=
d reason to believe you, you might not be guilty of fraud.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">You could imagine more complicated variants. For instance, =
your company could have a written business plan that says =E2=80=9Cthe plan=
 is to spend all the money we raise at restaurants and casinos,=E2=80=9D an=
d it could have audited financial statements showing zero revenue, millions=
 of cash inflows from investors, and identical outflows to restaurants and =
casinos. And then when potential investors heard your pitch and said =E2=80=
=9Cokay send me your business plan and financial statements,=E2=80=9D you c=
ould say =E2=80=9Cno, those are too secret to share with investors, but tru=
st me they are very good.=E2=80=9D And then when you end up in court you ca=
n be like =E2=80=9Cwell, again, they=C2=A0<em>were=C2=A0</em>good, for me.=
=E2=80=9D And the investor =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look, it=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>ki=
nd of bad for the investor to give you money without seeing the financials?=
 Like, sure you told them that they couldn=E2=80=99t see the financials, bu=
t they could have walked away at that point! At some point, if someone want=
s to be defrauded badly enough, it is almost not fraud to take their money?=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the New York Times,=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25625218.276657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
bnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8xMS8wNC90ZWNobm9sb2d5L3RoZXJhbm9zLWVsaXphYmV0aC1ob2x=
tZXMtaW52ZXN0b3JzLWRpbGlnZW5jZS5odG1sP3NtdHlwPWN1ciZzbWlkPXR3LW55dGltZXNidX=
NpbmVzcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d0c9945" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Erin Griffith had a fun=
ny story</a> about the fraud trial of Theranos Inc. founder Elizabeth Holme=
s:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As investors have testified =
at Ms. Holmes=E2=80=99s trial, a central tension has emerged around due dil=
igence. Could these investors have avoided disaster if they had simply done=
 better research on Theranos? Or were they doomed because their research wa=
s based on lies? ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ms. Holmes=E2=80=99s l=
awyers have needled Theranos=E2=80=99s investors for their oversights, aimi=
ng to convince the jury that the investors were the ones at fault for not d=
igging into Ms. Holmes=E2=80=99 claims. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The strategy has sometimes veered into condescension. That was evide=
nt last week when Lance Wade, a lawyer for Ms. Holmes, asked [DeVos family-=
office investment manager Lisa]=C2=A0Peterson, an investment professional, =
if she was familiar with the concept of due diligence.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou understand that=E2=80=99s a typical thing to do in=
 investing?=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Ch=
ristopher] Lucas=E2=80=99s firm, Black Diamond Ventures, invested around $7=
 million into Theranos, despite not getting access to its financial informa=
tion or examining all of its corporate records. This was unusual, Mr. Lucas=
 testified on Thursday, but Ms. Holmes told him the information was sensiti=
ve because a leak could =E2=80=9Cgive competitors a chance to crush the com=
pany.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That secrecy extended to due=
 diligence. Ms. Peterson testified that she was scared Ms. Holmes would cut=
 her firm out of the deal if they dug deeper into the details of Theranos=
=E2=80=99s business.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe were very =
careful not to circumvent things and upset Elizabeth,=E2=80=9D she said. =
=E2=80=9CIf we did too much, we wouldn=E2=80=99t be invited back to invest.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of this stuff =
comes down to market norms, on both sides. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/25625218.276657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMDYvZG9nZWNvaW4taXMtdXAtYmVjYXVzZS1pdC1zL=
WZ1bm55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDgyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nv=
dXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTEwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe33639b2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Part of Holmes=E2=80=99s defens=
e</a> is =E2=80=9Cthat exaggeration is part of Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s sta=
rtup culture=E2=80=9D: Sure she did a certain amount of fake-it-till-you-ma=
ke-it, but everyone in startups does that and investors could not have been=
 deceived by it. But part of the argument=C2=A0<em>against=C2=A0</em>her is=
 that her investors=C2=A0<em>did </em>justifiably rely on her sketchy pitch=
, without pushing to do real due diligence, because in a deal world driven =
by fear of missing out on the next big thing, that was actually a normal wa=
y for an investor to operate.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=
